FORCED MOVES -- Miriam's defensive play in games of form M1 shows her
achieving a tie by following a sequence of forced moves.  The inference
I draw is that when she fails to make a forced move it is because
she is pursuing some non-defensive objective (as is clearly the case
in game 1.5).
GAME KNOWLEDGE -- Miriam knew well that achieving a fork guarantees
victory.  She knew of one specific forking pattern, the three corner fork.
There is no evidence that she knew of any other.  In offensive play,
Miriam was capable of an expert win in opening form M2, apparently
without recognizing tha fork her procedure effected.  Her expert wins 
in form M2 do not necessarily indicate that she was even aware
of the forks her play established.  She showed no knowledge
of possible expert wins with openings C1 and C2.  Her defensive
play showed no appreciation that the side response to a middle opening
is a pitfall (form M2) as is the adjacent corner response to a corner
opening form C3).
REPRESENTATION -- Miriam did not represent a fork as two intersecting
"ways-to-win", i.e. her representation of the three corner fork did not
include "what isn't there", the requirement that specific cells be
empty.  This judgment (based on game 1.5) is reinforced by Miriam's
attempt to block the three corner fork by seizing corner cells (game 2.3).
RIGIDITY -- Whenever Miriam embarked on a corner opening, she expected
or, better, desperately hoped that one particular game would result 
(the successful trap of form C5).  Games 1.4 and 2.4 show she had no idea
of how to counter an opposite corner response to a corner opening.
LEARNING FROM AN OPPONENT'S PLAY -- After suffering herself
two different ways of frustrating the three corner fork, Miriam
applied neither as a defense against it.
