     The basic representational challenge is to relate a cognitive structure
to the recorded play in such a way that the functioning of the structure
"explains" the observed behavior.  I choose the representation set forth in
Figure 1-1.  Somehow is presented QUERY, a question, "What move next?", and information
(the markers already in place in the grid) to those structures which determine behavior.
Miriam did not attempt to make every move, only those of her turn.  This obvious
fact requires some control element, represented by "TURNS", which inhibits taking
the opponent's turn.  Since the choice of who moves first is a special case of
whose move is next, it seems appropriate to cluster those questions together.

     What happens when it is not the opponent's turn ?  Control passes
to a cluster of structures I call microworlds.  Each microworld responds to
a situation it can recognize.  The "recognition part" of a microworld is its
PERSPECTIVE.  When a pattern is recognized, a slot in the perspective is
filled. When the associated perspective slots are filled, the functions of a
microworld are activated and they execute, proposing an action.  For example,
in a microworld which blocks an opponent's winning, the recognition of the threat
implicit in opponent's markers in cells 1 and 4  results in proposing a move to cell 7.  Such a proposed move is effected if it is uncontested.

     What happens when more than one threat is recognized (as in a fork) or
when a threat-blocking proposal confronts a proposal to win the game by a 
different move ?  The answer to this question is a mixture of representation
choice and empirical observation.  I choose (for reasons which will appear
subsequently) to represent the structures which respond stepwise to developing
games as a set of three competing microworlds. One (WIN) recognizes ways to
to win.  A second (BLOCK) recognizes opponent's threats. The third (POSITION)
directs the next move when neither a win is immediately possible nor a threat
is recognized.  If three such microworlds compete with each other in responding
to a specific QUERY ( as I assume they do), the factors which affect that
competition and the functions within the POSITION-world are to be empirically
determined.

