     How should games 1.3 - 1.5 lead us to alter the structure of
Figure 1.1 ?  Should we merely assume that boredom led the TURNS frame to
reject middle openings ?  The answer must be "no", and for at least
two reasons.  First, the objective of the CORNERS microworld (for so
we will declare this other structure to be) is different in kind from
the stepwise tactical objectives which determine the functions of the
POSITION world.  We will call the objective a strategic one because it
aims at nothing less than winning the game through achieving a specific 
fork.  Secondly, the CORNERS-world does not interact with the three
competing microworlds of the stepwise cluster, i.e. the objectives of POSITION and CORNERS show alternative modes of play.  More specifically,  in games 1.5, the BLOCK-world function of blocking an opponent's threat did not operate.  In game 1.4, Miriam refused to continue play, i.e. she	 did not seek to enhance her position.  A critic might raise these questions: "Didn't she win game 1.3 ?  Doesn't that implicate some sort of connection with the WIN microworld ?"  Not so, for the character of the processes of winning is not uniform.  In the WIN-world, the perspective recognizes an unforced way to win among the patterns of various markers, while the victory achieved by the three corner gambit is pre-established as one of the two alternatives implicit in the fork.  It is little more than the immediate  consequence of achieving the CORNERS-world objective.  The more elaborate structure is diagrammed in Figure 1.2
