a higher level of control.  There is no place in the microworld's internal 
structure for the kind of knowledge Miriam expressed about Robby's play, i.e.
that he could prevent her from winning and would do so.  Miriam's knowledge of
his knowledge could not reach beyond what she knew herself.  (Indeed, she ascribes
to him the only strategy she owns.  This is appropriate, in fact, since what she learned 
of the three corner fork came from observing his play at the Children's Museum.)
Further, her fear he would prevent her getting "two-ways-to-win",i.e. block her
three corner fork, led her to modify her play significantly,  to abandon her
only offensive strategy for position enhancing tactics in 2.2.  The conclusion I infer is that Miriam's anticipation of Robby's play functioned through the frame to influence which of the two modes of play she followed.  That is, the tactical and strategic modes do not compete between themselves in the same sense as do microworlds of the stepwise cluster; not merely do they not interact, they are distinct alternatives between which a choice is made based upon the frame linked knowledge about "social" aspects of her opponent's play.  The objectives influencing which cluster of microworlds is activated are shown in the diagram of Figure 2-1 which completes the initial characterization of Miriam's Tic tac toe related structures at the beginning of The Intimate Study.
