     During the sessions represented by games sets three through nine,
Miriam was under instruction.  Though didactic with respect to my intentions,
these sessions were in no way formal.  The typical situation would place
Miriam in my lap; we would have just finished "doing some adding" and at
her request had taken up Tic tac toe.  Miriam provided most direction in
these sessions.  My instruction was usually a response to and a reflection
upon some immediately preceding action of hers.  My two general objectives
were to help Miriam understand and fix those faux pas -- those mis-steps
of her procedures -- and to develop her ablity to learn from an opponent.
     Miriam's apprenticeship -- defined more by my didactic intentions
than by any action or attitude of hers -- extended over four month's time.
I began as a casual player; no one should be surprised that my view of
Tic tac toe changed during this period.  With respect to the instruction
I offered Miriam, game sets three through five reflect the everyday view
of Tic tac toe.  Beginning with game set 6, my thinking and instruction
were dominated by the opening oriented view.
     Despite this varying perspective on the CONTENT on instruction, the
METHOD of instruction continually revolved around the idea of TURNING THE
TABLES on an opponent.  By turning the tables, I mean this sequence of events:
.ss
.nofill
.indent 1
1. Whenever Miriam lost a game or found a strategy frustrated,
2. we replayed that game with the roles of initiator and opponent reversed
3. so that she could copy and actively execute the winning procedure
4. during which re-execution we could (but did not always) discuss each move
and verify that she was copying it accurately.
.ds
